#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:18
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "This training unit introduces the Attitude Director Indicator instrument for the Shuttle-A. It runs for about 15 minutes. You can fast-forward through any sections with the 'T' and 'R' keys."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:25
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "The new 2-D panel of the Shuttle-A transport vessel has been equipped with a versatile new instrument: the Attitude Director Indicator (or ADI for short)."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:29
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "The ADI consists of a ball that represents the orientation of an attitude reference frame with respect to the current vessel orientation."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:35
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "\nWhen the vessel rotates, the ball remains aligned with the reference frame."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:52
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "The markings on the ball represent a grid of pitch and yaw lines ..."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:56
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "\n\n... and the current vessel pitch and yaw in the reference frame can be read off from the center marker."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:63
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "The ring around the ball contains a scale for the roll angle, and the vessel's current roll angle is indicated with a red marker."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:74
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "The spacecraft's current roll, pitch and yaw angles with respect to the reference frame are also shown on the 'DEV' line in the digital display below the ADI."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:80
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "You have a choice of attitude reference frames to select from. The most suitable frame depends on the particular maneuver or flight phase you are currently executing."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:86
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "The controls for selecting the reference frame, as well as a number of other functions relating to the attitude reference and ADI operation, are located in the panel below the ADI."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:92
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "\n\nThe attitude frame can be selected with the 'FRAME' dial."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:98
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "'ECL' stands for ecliptic frame: The plane of the ecliptic is represented by the (pitch=0) plane. The vernal equinox is represented by the (pitch=0,yaw=0) direction, and the ecliptic north pole is represented by the (pitch=+90) direction."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:105
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "'EQU' stands for equatorial frame: The equatorial plane of the body we are in orbit around is represented by the (pitch=0) plane. The ascending node of the ecliptic is represented by the (pitch=0,yaw=0) direction, and the positive (north) direction of the planet's rotation axis is represented by the (pitch=+90) direction."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:112
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "'OV/OM' stands for orbital velocity / orbital moment vector. Unlike the previous two frames, this is not an inertial frame. Instead it rotates as our spacecraft proceeds along its orbital trajectory. The direction of the orbital velocity vector (relative to the body being orbited) is represented by the (pitch=0,yaw=0) axis. The direction of the orbital moment vector (perpendicular to the orbital plane) is represented by the (pitch=0,yaw=270) axis. If the orbit is circular, then the (pitch=0) plane represents the local horizon plane. The OV/OM frame is equivalent to the 'Orbit' HUD mode, but with a 90 degree roll offset."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:119
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "'LH/LN' stands for local horizon / local north. Like OV/OM, this is a rotating frame. The (pitch=0) plane represents the local horizon, and the (pitch=0,yaw=0) direction is the north direction in the horizon plane. The (pitch=-90) direction points towards the centre of the planet, and (pitch=+90) points away from it. This frame is equivalent to the 'Surface' HUD mode."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:126
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "'NAV 1' and 'NAV 2' are special modes. They feed data from the Nav-1 and Nav-2 receivers to the ADI. The reference frame depends on the type of transmitter the radio is currently tuned to. For example, if the radio is tuned to an IDS (instrument docking system) transmitter, then the ADI ball is aligned with the docking approach direction."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:133
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "All of the predefined frames can be modified by adding offsets to the roll, pitch and yaw angles. This will rotate the reference frame against the frame of the base mode."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:140
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "\n\nThe 'OFFSET' button group can be used to define the offset angles."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:146
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "Make sure that the 'FRM/TGT' selector switch is set to 'FRM'. This will add the offsets to the reference frame, rather than the target (which will be discussed later)."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:152
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "Use the 'R', 'P' and 'Y' toggles to add or subtract offsets in the roll, pitch and yaw angles."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:176
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "The current offset angles (in degrees) are shown in the 'OFS' line of the digital display."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:182
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "To remove the frame offsets, press the 'RESET' button."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:192
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "The ADI ball also contains two 'error needles' (the horizontal and vertical red bars) which can be used to designate a direction in the reference frame."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:200
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "The target mode can be selected with the 'TARGET' dial."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:206
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "'NONE' simply disables the target mode and centers the error needles on the ball."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:212
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "\n\nThe 'TGT' indicator on the ADI ball instrument displays 'OFF'."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:218
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "'FIXED' marks a fixed pitch/yaw point in the reference frame. By default, this is the (pitch=0,yaw=0) direction ..."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:225
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "\n\n... but you can select any pitch/yaw direction by adding offsets."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:231
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "Make sure that the 'FRM/TGT' selector switch is set to 'TGT'. This will add the offsets to the target direction, rather than the reference frame."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:241
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "Then use the 'P' and 'Y' toggles to add or subtract offsets to the target direction pitch and yaw angles. Note that the 'R' (roll) toggle is inactive in this mode."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:260
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "The current target offset angles (in degrees) are shown in the 'OFS' line of the digital display."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:266
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "As with the reference frame, target offsets can be removed by pressing the 'RESET' button."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:276
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "Note that the error needles indicate not only the direction towards the target, but also the opposite direction, away from the target. To distinguish between the two, the 'TGT' indicator on the ADI shows 'TO' or 'FROM'."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:291
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "In addition to the fixed target direction, the ADI can also dynamically display the bearing of a NAV radio transmitter. To activate this mode, first set the 'FRAME' selector to NAV 1 or NAV 2, and make sure that the corresponding receiver is tuned to a transmitter in range."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:297
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "\n\nIn this case, NAV 1 has been tuned to the IDS (instrument docking system) frequency of the nearby ISS."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:303
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "Next, set the 'TARGET' dial to 'N. BRG' (NAV bearing)."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:311
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "When the ADI is slaved to a receiver tuned to an IDS signal, and the target mode is set to bearing information, the ADI indicator acts similarly to the 'Docking' MFD mode, where the ball takes the role of the MFD's attitude alignment indicator (x), and the error needles take the role of the lateral offset indicator (+)."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:323
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "When you have the ball aligned at (R=0,P=0,Y=0), and the error needles are centered, you are located on the correct approach path to the dock, with the correct vessel attitude."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:327
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "\n\n(You can try this later. First let's finish the description of the ADI functions.)"
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:332
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "The remaining target mode is 'N. Vel'. Like, N. Brg, this is mode relies on data from a Nav receiver, so the frame mode must be set to Nav 1 or Nav 2, and the associated receiver must be tuned to a transmitter."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:340
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "\n\nIn this mode however, the target direction is given by the relative velocity between the target transmitter and yourself, expressed in the reference frame."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:345
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "This mode is useful for judging your approach towards a dock, landing pad, VOR transmitter, etc."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:350
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "For example, if you are tuned to an IDS or XPDR transmitter, then the N. Vel direction is equivalent to the velocity markers in the Docking HUD mode."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:357
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "The final component of the ADI are the rate indicators. These are the scales at the top, bottom and right edges of the instrument."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:366
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "The top scale indicates the current roll rate..."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:375
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "\n\n...the scale on the right shows the current pitch rate..."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:385
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "\n\n...and the bottom scale shows the current yaw rate."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:395
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "\n\nEach scale tick mark represents a rate of 2deg./s with a range of +/- 10 degrees in each axis."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:400
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "The rates can be displayed in two different frames: Either in the local spacecraft frame, where the rates are directly related to the RCS thrusters for the corresponding axis..."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:410
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "\n\n...or the current ADI reference frame, where the rates correspond to the rotation of the ball.\n\nThe frames can be selected with the 'RATE' switch on the control panel."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:417
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "You may come across the ADI ball in two different layouts. So far we have used a ball that uses the pitch=0 plane as the plane of reference, with poles at pitch = +/-90 degrees. The range of yaw angles is 0-360 degrees."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:421
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "An alternative layout uses the yaw = 0 plane as plane of reference, with poles at yaw = +/-90, and pitch range 0-360 degrees."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:429
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "\n\nThis is the layout used by the ADI instrument in Apollo and pre-glass cockpit Space Shuttle spacecraft."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:433
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "Note that the two layouts only differ in the markings printed on the ball, not in the way the ball behaves."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:437
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "\n\nIt is important to remember that the definitions of the Euler angles (roll, pitch, yaw) in the two layouts are different."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:441
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "\n\nTherefore, the same spacecraft orientation will result in two different sets of Euler angles depending on the chosen layout."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:445
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "The layout can be selected by adding an ADI_LAYOUT 0/1 entry in the Shuttle-A's scenario definition, or with the V:set_adilayout function in a terminal MFD."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:449
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "This concludes the introduction of the ADI. Got everything? If not, have a look at Doc\\ShuttleA.pdf, section 'Reference frame and ADI'."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:452
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "\n\nOtherwise, let's have a little test to see if you have mastered the ADI yet..."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:457
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "I am going to turn off the MFDs and HUD. You should rely on the ADI only."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:544
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "Wrong dock! You must dock at port 1 to pass this test."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:558 C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:579
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "Here is the first task: Turn your vessel to a prograde direction and hold."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:566
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "Do you want to make me angry?"
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:566
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "I can fail you for this, you know."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:566
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "That would be cheating. Please don't push this button again during this task."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:566
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "You seem to have serious attitude problems ..."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:566
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "That's it, test failed for obnoxious behaviour. If you want to retake it, you'll have to go through the tutorial again."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:577
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "Script terminated."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:584
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "Task 1 passed!"
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:588
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "The next task: Turn your vessel towards the vernal equinox and hold. (The vernal equinox is the ascending node of the ecliptic with respect to Earth's equatorial plane.)"
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:594
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "Task 2 passed!"
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:598
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "The next task: Turn your vessel towards the celestial south pole and hold. (The celestial south pole is the negative of Earth's spin axis direction.)"
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:604
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "Task 3 passed!"
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:608
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "Now, turn your vessel towards Sirius. Sirius has the following celestial coordinates: Right ascension 6h 45m 9s, declination -16deg 42' 58''. (You may need pen and paper to convert these coordinates to decimal degrees.)\n\nTip: consider the direction in which right ascension coordinates are increasing."
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:614
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "Task 4 passed!"
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:618
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "All good so far. Here is the last test: Dock with the ISS, docking port 1. (NAV-1 has already been tuned to its IDS transmitter.)"
msgstr ""

#: C:/github/openorbiter/Src/Vessel/ShuttleA/Script/adi.lua:624
msgctxt "ShuttleA ADI tutorial"
msgid "Hard dock! You pass all tests and are now a certified ADI operator. Congratulations!"
msgstr ""

